    "headline": "Struggling Nike will cut around 1,400 jobs in efficiency push",
    "summary": "<body><p>STORY: Nike said on Thursday it is laying off about 1,400 people to streamline workflows.</p><p>As the struggling sportswear company fights through a years-long sales slump.</p><p>In a memo to employees on Thursday,&nbsp;the company said it would cut jobs in global operations, mainly technology.</p><p>It accounts for a little less than 2% of the global workforce.</p><p>Shares edged up about 0.5% in after-hours trading but shares have lost more than half their value in the last three years.</p><p>:: On</p><p>Nimbler competitors like On, Hoka and Anta have won more shelf space.</p><p>It is the latest in a string of job cuts.</p><p>Most recently 775 roles were axed in January in a bid to speed up automation.</p><p>:: Nike</p><p>CEO Elliott Hill, who took the helm in 2024 has vowed to re-center the brand.</p><p>Focusing on core sports like running and soccer, and bringing new and innovative shoes to market quickly.</p><p>However, efforts to wow the market with new, must-have sneakers have been inconsistent.</p><p>Analysts believe Nike should be further along in its recovery and the job losses are unsurprising.</p><p>According to the memo, the cuts will allow Nike to better integrate its supply chains and to focus its technology operations in two main hubs in Oregon&nbsp;and India.</p></body>",
